In a hexagonal spiral, each number has two neighbors on the same ring: the previous and next in the spiral order.

Then, it has two neighbors on the same radial line: inward and outward.

Then, it has two neighbors that are "diagonal" — one on the previous side, one on the next side, at the same offset.

